@remark "manual page source format generated by PolyglotMan v3.2 available at http://polyglotman.sourceforge.net/"
@wordwrap
@tab 8

@node sect0 "Name"
samrename - rename a SAMDOS file or files 
@endnode

@node sect1 "Synopsis"
@{b}samerase [@{ub} @{b}-diskfile @{ub}@{i}file@{ui} ] sourcename [to] destname 
@endnode

@node sect2 "Description"
@{i}Samrename@{ui} renames  a file or files on a SAMDOS diskette.  The filenames will be displayed as they are renamed.  Wildcard characters are allowed in the filenames.  The use of wildcards or spaces will require the names to be enclosed in quotes to protect them from the shell. @{i}Samrename@{ui} may be used to rename files in a disk image rather than a real floppy by setting the environment variable SAMDISKFILE to the name of the image file or by supplying the @{b}-diskfile @{ub}@{i}file@{ui} flag.  If used this flag must be written first on the command line. It may be abbreviated to @{b}-disk @{ub}@{i}file.@{ui} 

If the destination name contains wildcard characters, there must be enough wildcards in the source name to match up.  The new name of each file to be renamed will be made up by adding together the non-wild characters in the destination name and the characters which matched the wildcards in the source name.  For example: 

@{b}samrename "fred?.*" "joe?-*"@{ub} 

will rename "fred2.bin" to "joe2-bin". 

If the disk is in MasterDOS format then full path names may be specified for the source and destination names.  See @{i}samtools@{ui}(1) for further information about directories.  In order to move some files from one directory to another, specify a wildcard that matches the files to be moved as the first argument and the directory name with a trailing slash character as the second argument.  A destination name of '' names the current directory.  


@endnode

@node sect3 "See Also"
samtools(1) 
@endnode

@node sect4 "Bugs"
If the new name for a file is longer than 10 characters it will just be truncated. 
@endnode
